238
00:15:53,439 --> 00:15:56,222
So make sure that you get your messaging on point as well.

239
00:15:56,222 --> 00:15:57,884
So we're all learning.

240
00:16:00,280 --> 00:16:05,704
Follow up, if you send out a press release and people don't cover your game, give it

241
00:16:05,704 --> 00:16:11,648
a couple of weeks and then ask, hey I sent you a press release, I know you didn't cover

242
00:16:11,648 --> 00:16:13,789
it, can you tell me why?

243
00:16:13,789 --> 00:16:18,832
You will probably only get one, two, three responses, but you will get some, and those

244
00:16:18,832 --> 00:16:22,495
responses will be incredibly useful.

245
00:16:22,495 --> 00:16:28,799
If they did cover your game, you want to message them and say...

246
00:16:29,109 --> 00:16:34,753
Hey, thanks for covering my game and give them more meat.

247
00:16:34,753 --> 00:16:42,759
So for example, what we did when Cine got picked up by a lot of press is we then started pitching to them with other ideas.

248
00:16:42,759 --> 00:16:53,026
Hey, by the way, did you know that Cine was developed in China by AAA indie devs who have decided, AAA developers who've gone indie? How cool is that?

249
00:16:53,026 --> 00:16:54,847
They're like, yeah, that is cool.

250
00:16:55,451 --> 00:17:01,537
And suddenly, we had a few articles being written about this kind of story of these

251
00:17:01,537 --> 00:17:07,662
developers from Shanghai got together and, you know, a real kind of Robin Hood story.

252
00:17:07,662 --> 00:17:08,243
Great.

253
00:17:08,243 --> 00:17:09,364
Excellent branding.

254
00:17:09,364 --> 00:17:16,450
So what is interesting or exciting, not just about your game, but about you?

255
00:17:17,054 --> 00:17:20,275
What story are you trying to tell for your companies?

256
00:17:20,275 --> 00:17:22,096
Because remember, if you're making a game,

257
00:17:22,096 --> 00:17:23,477
it's not just about that game,

258
00:17:23,477 --> 00:17:24,817
it's also about your next game,

259
00:17:24,817 --> 00:17:26,858
and the game after that, and the game after that.

260
00:17:26,858 --> 00:17:28,859
So you wanna be building up this narrative

261
00:17:28,859 --> 00:17:30,019
about who you are.

262
00:17:30,019 --> 00:17:32,720
If you want the perfect example of this,

263
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:34,001
look at Devolver Digital.

264
00:17:34,001 --> 00:17:38,082
They did an amazing job of creating a brand for themselves

265
00:17:38,082 --> 00:17:44,264
as these cheeky, rude, naughty games publishers.

266
00:17:44,264 --> 00:17:46,465
And they've maintained that brand for,

267
00:17:47,034 --> 00:17:51,136
nearly ten years now, and it's done very well for them.

268
00:17:51,136 --> 00:17:52,517
So think about that.

269
00:17:52,517 --> 00:17:57,580
How are you positioning yourself and how are you making yourself stand out, not just your

270
00:17:57,580 --> 00:17:57,840
game?

271
00:17:57,840 --> 00:18:03,463
And the next step is the launch date announcement.

272
00:18:03,463 --> 00:18:08,586
So the first thing you want to do is say, hey, we have a game.

273
00:18:08,586 --> 00:18:14,509
Don't give a launch date unless you are certain you know that launch date, okay?

274
00:18:14,509 --> 00:18:16,070
This is another mistake I have made.

275
00:18:16,572 --> 00:18:21,595
we announced the launch date and then we decided to postpone.

276
00:18:21,595 --> 00:18:26,018
Very dangerous people do not like this.

277
00:18:26,018 --> 00:18:31,260
We actually made the right decision because we announced the launch date before the Nintendo

278
00:18:31,260 --> 00:18:34,442
Switch came out, and then the Nintendo Switch came out and we went,

279
00:18:34,442 --> 00:18:37,424
yeah, we want some of that Nintendo love.

280
00:18:37,424 --> 00:18:39,445
And it worked out very well for us.

281
00:18:39,445 --> 00:18:39,925
But...

282
00:18:40,812 --> 00:18:43,573
Be very careful with that because this can backfire a lot.

283
00:18:43,573 --> 00:18:45,634
So do not announce a launch date until you know

284
00:18:45,634 --> 00:18:47,794
that you've got that launch date.

285
00:18:47,794 --> 00:18:51,075
You need another trailer, you need another press release.

286
00:18:51,075 --> 00:18:53,556
So your press release needs to give obviously

287
00:18:53,556 --> 00:18:58,657
the date, the time, but also needs to give more details.

288
00:18:58,657 --> 00:18:59,778
So remember this, don't give away everything

289
00:18:59,778 --> 00:19:00,718
in the first point.

290
00:19:00,718 --> 00:19:03,799
Don't lay out your life story in the first press release.

291
00:19:03,799 --> 00:19:05,960
You have to keep information back.

292
00:19:05,960 --> 00:19:08,220
You have to hold back and you have to give it out

293
00:19:08,220 --> 00:19:08,700
at certain times.

294
00:19:09,222 --> 00:19:12,185
At this point, you need to start doing your influencer outreach as well.

295
00:19:12,185 --> 00:19:18,009
If you haven't already started it, at this point, you need to be doing influencer outreach.

296
00:19:18,009 --> 00:19:24,034
Six weeks before launch, you need to launch the press release, Embargoed, and then on

297
00:19:24,034 --> 00:19:29,999
the actual launch day, you need to have, again, another trailer and more information.

298
00:19:29,999 --> 00:19:30,459
Okay?

299
00:19:30,459 --> 00:19:33,101
Can you explain a bit more about Embargoed?

300
00:19:33,101 --> 00:19:34,482
Because this is a term that we...

301
00:19:35,572 --> 00:19:43,998
Okay, so embargo is basically you send an email to a press organization saying,

302
00:19:43,998 --> 00:19:49,983
here is a copy of my game for review, do not release the review until X date.

303
00:19:49,983 --> 00:19:59,190
Because you don't want, if you launch your game, so if you give press your game six weeks in advance,

304
00:19:59,190 --> 00:20:01,452
you don't want review.

305
00:20:02,572 --> 00:20:06,535
three days, review, two days, review, three days, review, four days, review, because it

306
00:20:06,535 --> 00:20:11,559
just spreads it out too much. Because what you need is one big punch. So you want to

307
00:20:11,559 --> 00:20:17,984
make sure that all of those reviews are coming out at the same time. So that's what embargoes

308
00:20:17,984 --> 00:20:24,068
allow you to do. And by and large, press quite like embargoes that I've given ahead, because

309
00:20:24,068 --> 00:20:28,892
it gives them time. Because right now, that's the big problem for games journalists, is

310
00:20:28,892 --> 00:20:29,653
just that...

311
00:20:29,993 --> 00:20:31,254
There are so many games.

312
00:20:31,254 --> 00:20:35,154
So the more time you give them, the more likely you are

313
00:20:35,154 --> 00:20:36,935
to actually get coverage.

314
00:20:36,935 --> 00:20:43,356
One note, influencers are really bad with embargoes.

315
00:20:43,356 --> 00:20:45,036
Really bad with embargoes.

316
00:20:45,036 --> 00:20:48,057
So it's a good idea to maybe do the press

317
00:20:48,057 --> 00:20:51,597
and then two weeks before launch, release to influencers.

318
00:20:51,597 --> 00:20:56,078
Because influencers get far too excited.

319
00:20:56,078 --> 00:20:57,498
And usually don't have the same kind of

320
00:20:57,498 --> 00:20:58,878
professional training.

321
00:20:59,255 --> 00:21:00,836
that a games journalist will have.

322
00:21:00,836 --> 00:21:07,121
Okay, what about community? Before you do anything you need to get your community

323
00:21:07,121 --> 00:21:08,201
stuff prepared. Like,

324
00:21:08,201 --> 00:21:11,804
I have genuinely seen on multiple occasions

325
00:21:11,804 --> 00:21:16,668
people doing all of this

326
00:21:16,668 --> 00:21:19,750
all of their marketing stuff and then

327
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:23,993
launching Facebook, Twitter, and things two weeks before their games come out.

328
00:21:23,993 --> 00:21:28,676
This is craziness. Do you guys know what a market funnel is?

329
00:21:31,661 --> 00:21:34,882
So a funnel is, I don't have anywhere to draw, do I?

330
00:21:34,882 --> 00:21:38,963
So imagine that you are trying to get water

331
00:21:38,963 --> 00:21:41,023
from a big thing into a little thing,

332
00:21:41,023 --> 00:21:43,644
and you are pouring it, okay?

333
00:21:43,644 --> 00:21:44,644
So you use a funnel, right?

334
00:21:44,644 --> 00:21:47,885
So what you want to do is you want to structure

335
00:21:47,885 --> 00:21:51,826
your marketing and community plan like a funnel.

336
00:21:51,826 --> 00:21:57,307
Every time you do an announcement or do a release,

337
00:21:57,307 --> 00:22:00,928
you need to pick one place.

338
00:22:01,573 --> 00:22:07,355
where you want all of those interested people to end up.

339
00:22:07,355 --> 00:22:12,757
So for example, it used to be Facebook, like I said, that used to be when I first got into

340
00:22:12,757 --> 00:22:15,238
the business, that's where everybody wanted everyone to be.

341
00:22:15,238 --> 00:22:20,980
You put them to Facebook, but then Facebook changed its monetisation structure and even

342
00:22:20,980 --> 00:22:25,662
if people like your page, there's no guarantee they will see your post.

343
00:22:25,662 --> 00:22:28,683
So suddenly Facebook became not very useful.

344
00:22:29,167 --> 00:22:35,010
So what we have now is we have Twitter, Facebook, Instagram, all of these things, but all of

345
00:22:35,010 --> 00:22:40,373
those things are designed to push people towards the Discord.

346
00:22:40,373 --> 00:22:46,857
So when we pour out the news, people get caught in our social media.

347
00:22:46,857 --> 00:22:51,159
So we get X number of people, X number of people, X number of people in our social media.

348
00:22:51,159 --> 00:22:55,602
And then the really committed people, the ones who really like the game...

349
00:22:56,224 --> 00:23:02,766
go into our Discord, because that's how we've got it set up. We have links to the Discord and all those things, okay?

350
00:23:02,766 --> 00:23:10,910
And then you end up with, for every announcement, a few hundred people who really fucking like your game.

351
00:23:10,910 --> 00:23:18,393
Who have gone through a couple of stages to get there, they're excited to talk to the developers, they're committed to the idea,

352
00:23:18,393 --> 00:23:20,374
and those people are so important.

353
00:23:21,807 --> 00:23:26,870
So yeah, like I said, you need to have your social media prepared before you do any announcements,

354
00:23:26,870 --> 00:23:29,811
before you release a screenshot, before you send a message to anyone.

355
00:23:29,811 --> 00:23:33,233
You need to have social media, community stuff set up.

356
00:23:33,233 --> 00:23:36,535
Pick a home for your community, okay?

357
00:23:36,535 --> 00:23:41,477
If you're not going to use Discord, find something else but commit to it, okay?

358
00:23:41,477 --> 00:23:48,181
Some people still use forums, you know, it's not a bad idea, it's just a pain in the ass.

359
00:23:48,892 --> 00:23:55,214
and get some moderators and do not forget about time zones.

360
00:23:55,214 --> 00:24:01,816
I remember when me and Vlad, we first opened our Discord and we were like,

361
00:24:01,816 --> 00:24:08,099
oh this is great, this is great. Me and Vlad, we'll monitor it all day, it's gonna be perfect.

362
00:24:08,099 --> 00:24:08,479
We live in Asia.

363
00:24:08,479 --> 00:24:14,421
So when all the Americans wake up and you get some horrible, horrible American boy

364
00:24:14,421 --> 00:24:17,482
who wants to post Nazi memes and pornography,

365
00:24:20,222 --> 00:24:27,565
So make sure that you're thinking like, okay, have somebody in that community promoted.

366
00:24:27,565 --> 00:24:35,108
If you manage to get 100 people in your Discord, you have 3 or 4 people who are desperate to be moderators.

367
00:24:35,108 --> 00:24:36,809
Who are desperate to get involved.

368
00:24:36,809 --> 00:24:42,311
Say, I will give you free copies of all of our games for as long as you are a moderator.

369
00:24:42,311 --> 00:24:45,453
Happy. Happy. Happy, happy people.

370
00:24:46,952 --> 00:24:50,174
Make sure you include your community in all press releases.

371
00:24:50,174 --> 00:24:53,876
Most press will not say, go to the Discord,

372
00:24:53,876 --> 00:24:55,757
or go to this, or go to that.

373
00:24:55,757 --> 00:24:57,237
But some will.

374
00:24:57,237 --> 00:24:59,298
And it has a massive impact.

375
00:24:59,298 --> 00:25:02,740
I think we had a Rock Paper Shotgun article once

376
00:25:02,740 --> 00:25:05,622
that included a link to our Discord,

377
00:25:05,622 --> 00:25:09,183
and suddenly our Discord grew by like 400 people.

378
00:25:09,183 --> 00:25:09,484
Just boom.

379
00:25:09,484 --> 00:25:12,805
Exciting.

380
00:25:12,805 --> 00:25:14,586
Run competitions.

381
00:25:15,632 --> 00:25:17,974
do things to interact with your community.

382
00:25:17,974 --> 00:25:22,257
So in the Another Indie server right now, we do

383
00:25:22,257 --> 00:25:25,259
Netflix Movie Night, where we just say

384
00:25:25,259 --> 00:25:29,522
at this time we will be watching this movie. Join us.

385
00:25:29,522 --> 00:25:33,105
And so people who are bored, because they must be very bored,

386
00:25:33,105 --> 00:25:35,907
will say cool. And so last weekend

387
00:25:35,907 --> 00:25:39,650
me, Vlad, and about 30 people from our Discord

388
00:25:39,650 --> 00:25:41,931
we watched Hellraiser.

389
00:25:42,842 --> 00:25:45,304
and just chatted like, oh, he's gonna kill her,

390
00:25:45,304 --> 00:25:45,964
oh, she's dead.

391
00:25:45,964 --> 00:25:48,765
And people love it, you know?

392
00:25:48,765 --> 00:25:51,507
Everyone's sharing Hellraiser memes,

393
00:25:51,507 --> 00:25:54,549
everybody's chatting, and it just gives that community

394
00:25:54,549 --> 00:25:57,370
that little bit more of, we're not just here

395
00:25:57,370 --> 00:25:57,970
to sell you shit.

396
00:25:57,970 --> 00:26:01,612
Obviously, in the end, you want your community

397
00:26:01,612 --> 00:26:04,774
to be a part of your sales strategy,

398
00:26:04,774 --> 00:26:07,836
but you also want it to be an actual community.

399
00:26:07,836 --> 00:26:10,457
Otherwise, people get bored very, very quickly.

400
00:26:11,421 --> 00:26:14,684
So yeah, we do that, and we also do competitions.

401
00:26:14,684 --> 00:26:16,345
We do loads of competitions.

402
00:26:16,345 --> 00:26:19,007
You know the Humble subscription?

403
00:26:19,007 --> 00:26:21,709
You pay like, what is it, $15 a month,

404
00:26:21,709 --> 00:26:25,672
and you get access to games every month, like Steam Keys?

405
00:26:25,672 --> 00:26:29,796
Humble's monthly fee is the payment method.

406
00:26:29,796 --> 00:26:30,636
Yeah, well, he said.

407
00:26:30,636 --> 00:26:34,479
We do that, and we have one just for our Discord.

408
00:26:34,479 --> 00:26:37,442
So what we do is we get all of those keys every month,

409
00:26:37,442 --> 00:26:38,843
and we run competitions for them.

